# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] In the fields of information technology and systems management, **application performance management** (**APM**) is the monitoring and management of the performance and availability of software applications.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] APM strives to detect and diagnose complex application performance problems to maintain an expected level of service.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The term monitoring was replaced by many tool vendors by the term Observability.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Often, monitoring is seen as the technical process of data collection, whereas observability is seen as the capability to understand a systems behavior.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Two sets of performance metrics are closely monitored.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The first set of performance metrics defines the performance experienced by end-users of the application.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] One example of performance is average response times under peak load.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The second set of performance metrics measures the computational resources used by the application for the load, indicating whether there is adequate capacity to support the load, as well as possible locations of a performance bottleneck.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Measurement of these quantities establishes an empirical performance baseline for the application.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The baseline can then be used to detect changes in performance.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Changes in performance can be correlated with external events and subsequently used to predict future changes in application performance.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The use of APM is common for Web applications, which lends itself best to the more detailed monitoring techniques.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] In addition to measuring response time for a user, response times for components of a Web application can also be monitored to help pinpoint causes of delay.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] There also exist HTTP appliances that can decode transaction-specific response times at the Web server layer of the application.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Measuring application performance causes overhead, that might also influence the user experience.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The overhead can be reduced by several technical measures, including reducing the amount of monitored events and aggregation of data before serialization.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Since the first half of 2013, APM has entered into a period of intense competition in technology and strategy with a multiplicity of vendors and viewpoints.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] This has caused an upheaval in the marketplace with vendors from unrelated backgrounds (including network monitoring, systems management, application instrumentation, and web performance monitoring) adopting messaging around APM.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] As a result, the term APM has become diluted and has evolved into a concept for managing application performance across many diverse computing platforms, rather than a single market.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] With so many vendors to choose from, selecting one can be a challenge.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] It is important to evaluate each carefully to ensure its capabilities meet your needs.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Two challenges for implementing APM are (1) it can be difficult to instrument an application to monitor application performance, especially among components of an application, and (2) applications can be virtualized, which increases the variability of the measurements.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] To alleviate the first problem application service management (ASM) provides an application-centric approach, where business service performance visibility is a key objective.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The second aspect present in distributed, virtual and cloud-based applications poses a unique challenge for application performance monitoring because most of the key system components are no longer hosted on a single machine.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Each function is now likely to have been designed as an Internet service that runs on multiple virtualized systems.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The applications themselves are very likely to be moving from one system to another to meet service-level objectives and deal with momentary outages.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Applications themselves are becoming increasingly difficult to manage as they move toward highly distributed, multi-tier, multi-element constructs that in many cases rely on application development frameworks such as .NET or Java.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The APM Conceptual Framework was designed to help prioritize an approach on what to focus on first for quick implementation and overall understanding of the five-dimensional APM model.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The framework slide outlines three areas of focus for each dimension and describes their potential benefits.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Measuring the transit of traffic from user request to data and back again is part of capturing the end-user experience (EUE).
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] The outcome of this measuring is referred to as Real-time Application monitoring (aka Top-Down monitoring), which has two components, passive and active.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Passive monitoring is usually an agentless appliance implemented using network port mirroring.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] A key feature to consider is the ability to support multi-component analytics (e.g., database, client/browser).
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Active monitoring, on the other hand, consists of synthetic probes and web robots predefined to report system availability and business transactions.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Active monitoring is a good complement to passive monitoring; together, these two components help provide visibility into application health during off-peak hours when transaction volume is low.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] When preparing to implement a runtime application architecture, it is necessary to ensure that up/down monitoring is in place for all nodes and servers within the environment (aka, bottom-up monitoring).
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] This helps lay the foundation for event correlation and provides the basis for a general understanding of how network topologies interact with application architectures.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Focus on user-defined transactions or the URL page definitions that have some meaning to the business community.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] For example, if there are 200 to 300 unique page definitions for a given application, group them into 8–12 high-level categories.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] This allows for meaningful SLA reports, and provides trending information on application performance from a business perspective: start with broad categories and refine them over time.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] For a deeper understanding, see Business transaction management.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Deep dive component monitoring (DDCM) requires an agent installation and is generally targeted at middleware, focusing on web, application, and messaging servers.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] It should provide a real-time view of the J2EE and .NET stacks, tying them back to the user-defined business transactions.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] A robust monitor shows a clear path from code execution (e.g., spring and struts) to the URL rendered, and finally to the user request.
[src:red-method/application-performance-management] Since DDCM is closely related to the second dimension in the APM model, most products in this field also provide application discovery dependency mapping (ADDM) as part of their offering.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:red-method/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:red-method/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:red-method/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:red-method/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:red-method/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:red-method/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:red-method/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:red-method/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:red-method/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:red-method/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:red-method/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:red-method/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:red-method/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:red-method/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:red-method/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:red-method/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:red-method/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:red-method/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:red-method/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:red-method/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:red-method/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:red-method/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:red-method/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:red-method/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:red-method/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:red-method/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:red-method/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:red-method/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:red-method/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:red-method/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:red-method/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:red-method/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:red-method/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:red-method/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:red-method/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:red-method/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:red-method/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:red-method/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:red-method/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:red-method/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:red-method/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:red-method/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:red-method/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:red-method/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:red-method/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:red-method/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:red-method/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:red-method/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:red-method/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:red-method/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:red-method/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:red-method/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:red-method/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:red-method/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:red-method/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:red-method/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:red-method/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:red-method/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:red-method/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:red-method/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:red-method/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:red-method/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:red-method/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:red-method/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:red-method/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:red-method/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:red-method/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:red-method/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:red-method/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:red-method/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:red-method/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:red-method/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:red-method/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:red-method/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:red-method/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:red-method/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:red-method/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:red-method/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:red-method/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:red-method/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:red-method/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:red-method/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:red-method/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:red-method/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:red-method/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:red-method/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:red-method/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:red-method/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:red-method/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:red-method/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:red-method/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:red-method/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Site Reliability Engineering originated at Google with Benjamin Treynor Sloss, who founded SRE team in 2003.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] The concept expanded within the software development industry, leading various companies to employ site reliability engineers.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] By March 2016, Google had more than 1,000 site reliability engineers on staff.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Dedicated SRE teams are common at larger web development companies.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] In middle-sized and smaller companies, DevOps teams sometimes perform SRE, as well.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Organizations that have adopted the concept include Airbnb, Dropbox, IBM, LinkedIn, Netflix, and Wikimedia.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Site reliability engineers (SREs) are responsible for a combination of system availability, latency, performance, efficiency, change management, monitoring, emergency response, and capacity planning.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] SREs often have backgrounds in software engineering, systems engineering, and/or system administration.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] The focuses of SRE include automation, system design, and improvements to system resilience.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] SRE is considered a specific implementation of DevOps; focusing specifically on building reliable systems, whereas DevOps covers a broader scope of operations.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Despite having different focuses, some companies have rebranded their operations teams to SRE teams.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams collaborate with other departments within organizations to guide the implementation of the mentioned principles.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Kitchen Sink refers to the expansive and often unbounded scope of services and workflows that SRE teams oversee.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Unlike traditional roles with clearly defined boundaries, SREs are tasked with various responsibilities, including system performance optimization, incident management, and automation.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] This approach allows SREs to address multiple challenges, ensuring that systems run efficiently and evolve in response to changing demands and complexities.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Infrastructure SRE teams focus on maintaining and improving the reliability of systems that support other teams' workflows.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] While they sometimes collaborate with platform engineering teams, their primary responsibility is ensuring up-time, performance, and efficiency.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Platform teams, on the other hand, primarily develop the software and systems used across the organization.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] While reliability is a goal for both, platform teams prioritize creating and maintaining the tools and services used by internal stakeholders, whereas Infrastructure SRE teams are tasked with ensuring those systems run smoothly and meet reliability standards.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams utilize a variety of tools with the aim of measuring, maintaining, and enhancing system reliability.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] These tools play a role in monitoring performance, identifying issues, and facilitating proactive maintenance.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] For instance, Nagios Core is commonly employed for system monitoring and alerting, while Prometheus (software) is frequently used for collecting and querying metrics in cloud-native environments.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams dedicated to specific products or applications are common in large organizations.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] These teams are responsible for ensuring the reliability, scalability, and performance of key services.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] In larger companies, it's typical to have multiple SRE teams, each focusing on different products or applications, ensuring that each area receives specialized attention to meet performance and availability targets.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] In an embedded model, individual SREs or small SRE pairs are integrated within software engineering teams.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] These SREs collaborate with developers, applying core SRE principles—such as automation, monitoring, and incident response—directly to the software development lifecycle.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] This approach aims to enhance reliability, performance, and collaboration between SREs and developers.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Consulting SRE teams specialize in advising organizations on the implementation of SRE principles and practices.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Typically composed of seasoned SREs with a history across various implementations, these teams provide insights and guidance for specific organizational needs.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] In large organizations that have adopted SRE, a hybrid model is common.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] This model includes various implementations, such as multiple Product/Application SRE teams dedicated to addressing the specific reliability needs of different products.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] An Infrastructure SRE team may collaborate with a Platform engineering group to achieve shared reliability goals for a unified platform that supports all products and applications.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] Since 2014, the USENIX organization has hosted the annual SREcon conference, bringing together site reliability engineers from various industries.
[src:red-method/site-reliability-engineering] This conference is a platform for professionals to share knowledge, explore effective practices, and discuss trends in site reliability engineering.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] At GrafanaCon EU in March, we had the pleasure of introducing one of Grafana Labs’ newest team members, Tom Wilkie, who joined as VP, Product with the acquisition of Kausal.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] And he came bearing gifts: his popular talk about the RED Method of monitoring microservices, which he created in 2015.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] “It’s a way of building a checklist that goes through everything,” he said. “It helps you know what you don’t know.” But he pointed out that this method, while useful, is somewhat abstract.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] Applying it to memory, for instance, is hard. “Memory utilization is tricky.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] Do you count caches toward utilization?” he said. “Saturation of memory is kind of a weird one… And what is a memory error?
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] “Everyone should understand the error rate, the request rate, and then some distribution of latency for those requests,” Tom explained. “You model this for every single service in your architecture, and this gives you a nice, consistent view of how your architecture is behaving.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] Plus, he pointed out, “The RED Method is a good proxy to how happy your customers will be.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] If you’ve got a high error rate, that’s basically going through to your users and they’re getting page load errors.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] If you’ve got a high duration, your website is slow.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] Finally, Tom looked at a third method: The Four Golden Signals, which is from Google’s SRE book.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] This is basically the same as the RED Method, but includes saturation.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] Like how much it should be using, or how much is it allowed to use, as a proportion between 1 and 0.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] This gives you a measure of how ‘full’ your service is, or some proxy for how full your service is at least.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] Tom recommended using the USE and RED Methods together. “It’s like the RED Method is about caring about your users and how happy they are,” Tom said, “and the USE Method is about caring about your machines and how happy they are.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] It’s really just two different views on the same system.
[src:red-method/the-red-method-how-to-instrument-your-services] Watch Tom’s full talk in the video below.
[src:red-method/throughput] The **aggregate throughput** is the sum of the data rates that are delivered over all channels in a network.
[src:red-method/throughput] Throughput represents digital bandwidth consumption.
[src:red-method/throughput] The throughput of a communication system may be affected by various factors, including the limitations of the underlying physical medium, available processing power of the system components, end-user behavior, etc.
[src:red-method/throughput] When taking various protocol overheads into account, the useful rate of the data transfer can be significantly lower than the maximum achievable throughput; the useful part is usually referred to as goodput.
[src:red-method/throughput] Users of telecommunications devices, systems designers, and researchers into communication theory are often interested in knowing the expected performance of a system.
[src:red-method/throughput] From a user perspective, this is often phrased as either "which device will get my data there most effectively for my needs?", or "which device will deliver the most data per unit cost?".
[src:red-method/throughput] Systems designers often select the most effective architecture or design constraints for a system, which drive its final performance.
[src:red-method/throughput] In most cases, the benchmark of what a system is capable of, or its *maximum performance* is what the user or designer is interested in.
[src:red-method/throughput] The term *maximum throughput* is frequently used when discussing end-user maximum throughput tests.
[src:red-method/throughput] Maximum throughput is essentially synonymous with digital bandwidth capacity.
[src:red-method/throughput] Four different values are relevant in the context of maximum throughput are used in comparing the *upper limit* conceptual performance of multiple systems.
[src:red-method/throughput] They are *maximum theoretical throughput*, *maximum achievable throughput*, *peak measured throughput*, and *maximum sustained throughput*.
[src:red-method/throughput] These values represent different qualities, and care must be taken that the same definitions are used when comparing different *maximum throughput* values.
[src:red-method/throughput] Each bit must carry the same amount of information if throughput values are to be compared.
[src:red-method/throughput] Data compression can significantly alter throughput calculations, including generating values exceeding 100% in some cases.
[src:red-method/throughput] If the communication is mediated by several links in series with different bit rates, the maximum throughput of the overall link is lower than or equal to the lowest bit rate.
[src:red-method/throughput] The lowest value link in the series is referred to as the bottleneck.
[src:red-method/throughput] Maximum theoretical throughput is closely related to the channel capacity of the system, and is the maximum possible quantity of data that can be transmitted under ideal circumstances.
[src:red-method/throughput] In some cases, this number is reported as equal to the channel capacity, though this can be deceptive, as only non-packetized systems technologies can achieve this.
[src:red-method/throughput] Maximum theoretical throughput is more accurately reported taking into account format and specification overhead with best-case assumptions.
[src:red-method/throughput] The **asymptotic throughput** (less formal **asymptotic bandwidth**) for a packet-mode communication network is the value of the maximum throughput function, when the incoming network load approaches infinity, either due to a message size, or the number of data sources.
[src:red-method/throughput] As with other bit rates and data bandwidths, the asymptotic throughput is measured in bits per second (bit/s) or (rarely) bytes per second (B/s), where 1 B/s is 8 bit/s.
[src:red-method/throughput] Decimal prefixes are used, meaning that 1 Mbit/s is 1000000 bit/s.
[src:red-method/throughput] Asymptotic throughput is usually estimated by sending or simulating a very large message (sequence of data packets) through the network, using a greedy source and no flow control mechanism (i.e., UDP rather than TCP), and measuring the volume of data received at the destination node.
[src:red-method/throughput] Traffic load between other sources may reduce this maximum network path throughput.
[src:red-method/throughput] Alternatively, a large number of sources and sinks may be modeled, with or without flow control, and the aggregate maximum network throughput measured (the sum of traffic reaching its destinations).
[src:red-method/throughput] A well-known application of asymptotic throughput is in modeling point-to-point communication where message latency $T(N)$ is modeled as a function of message length N as $T(N)=(M+N)/A$ where A is the asymptotic bandwidth and M is the half-peak length.
[src:red-method/throughput] As well as its use in general network modeling, asymptotic throughput is used in modeling performance on massively parallel computer systems, where system operation is highly dependent on communication overhead, as well as processor performance.
[src:red-method/throughput] In these applications, asymptotic throughput is used modeling which includes the number of processors, so that both the latency and the asymptotic throughput are functions of the number of processors.
[src:red-method/throughput] Where asymptotic throughput is a theoretical or calculated capacity, *peak measured throughput* is throughput measured on a real implemented system, or on a simulated system.
[src:red-method/throughput] The value is the throughput measured over a short period of time; mathematically, this is the limit taken with respect to throughput as time approaches zero.
[src:red-method/throughput] This term is synonymous with *instantaneous throughput*.
[src:red-method/throughput] This number is useful for systems that rely on burst data transmission; however, for systems with a high duty cycle, this is less likely to be a useful measure of system performance.
[src:red-method/throughput] Maximum sustained throughput is the throughput averaged or integrated over a long time.
[src:red-method/throughput] For networks under constant load, this is likely to be the most accurate indicator of system performance.
[src:red-method/throughput] The maximum throughput is defined as the asymptotic throughput when the load is large.
[src:red-method/throughput] In packet-switched networks while packet loss is not occurring, the load and the throughput always are equal.
[src:red-method/throughput] The maximum throughput may be defined as the minimum load in bit/s that causes packet loss or causes the latency to become unstable and increase towards infinity.
[src:red-method/throughput] Throughput is sometimes normalized and measured in percentage, but normalization may cause confusion regarding what the percentage is related to.
[src:red-method/throughput] *Channel utilization*, *channel efficiency* and *packet drop rate* in percentage are less ambiguous terms.
[src:red-method/throughput] The channel efficiency, also known as bandwidth utilization efficiency, is the percentage of the net bit rate (in bit/s) of a digital communication channel that goes to the achieved throughput.
[src:red-method/throughput] For example, if the throughput is 70 Mbit/s over a 100 Mbit/s Ethernet connection, the channel efficiency is 70%.
[src:red-method/throughput] Channel utilization includes both the data bits and the transmission overhead in the channel.
[src:red-method/throughput] The transmission overhead consists of preamble sequences, frame headers and acknowledgment packets.
[src:red-method/throughput] In a simplistic approach, channel efficiency can be equal to channel utilization assuming that acknowledge packets are zero-length and that the communications provider will not see any bandwidth relative to retransmissions or headers.
[src:red-method/throughput] Therefore, certain texts mark a difference between channel utilization and protocol efficiency.
[src:red-method/throughput] For example, the maximum frame size in Ethernet is 1526 bytes: up to 1500 bytes for the payload, eight bytes for the preamble, 14 bytes for the header, and 4 bytes for the trailer.
[src:red-method/throughput] An additional minimum interframe gap corresponding to 12 bytes is inserted after each frame.
[src:red-method/throughput] This corresponds to a maximum channel utilization of 1526 / (1526 + 12) × 100% = 99.22%, or a maximum channel use of 99.22 Mbit/s inclusive of Ethernet datalink layer protocol overhead over a 100 Mbit/s Ethernet connection.
[src:red-method/throughput] The maximum throughput or channel efficiency is then 1500 / (1526 + 12) = 97.5%, exclusive of the Ethernet protocol overhead.
[src:red-method/throughput] The throughput of a communication system will be limited by a number of factors.
[src:red-method/throughput] The maximum achievable throughput (the channel capacity) is affected by the bandwidth in hertz and signal-to-noise ratio of the analog physical medium.
[src:red-method/throughput] Limited current drive capability in communications equipment can limit the effective signal-to-noise ratio for high capacitance links.
[src:red-method/throughput] Despite the conceptual simplicity of digital information, all electrical signals traveling over wires are analog.
[src:red-method/throughput] The analog limitations of wires or wireless systems inevitably provide an upper bound on the amount of information that can be sent.
[src:red-method/throughput] The dominant equation here is the Shannon–Hartley theorem, and analog limitations of this type can be understood as factors that affect either the analog bandwidth of a signal or as factors that affect the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:red-method/throughput] The bandwidth of twisted pair cabling used by Ethernet is limited to approximately 1 GHz, and PCB traces are limited by a similar amount.
[src:red-method/throughput] Digital systems refer to the *knee frequency*, the amount of time for the digital voltage to rise from 10% of a nominal digital 0 to a nominal digital 1 or vice versa.
[src:red-method/throughput] Large data loads that require processing impose data processing requirements on hardware.
[src:red-method/throughput] For example, a gateway router must examine and perform routing table lookups on billions of packets per second.
[src:red-method/throughput] CSMA/CD and CSMA/CA backoff waiting time and frame retransmissions after detected collisions slows transmissions.
[src:red-method/throughput] This may occur in Ethernet bus networks and hub networks, as well as in wireless networks.
[src:red-method/throughput] Flow control, for example, in the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) protocol, affects the throughput if the bandwidth-delay product is larger than the TCP window.
[src:red-method/throughput] In that case, the sending computer must wait for acknowledgement of the data packets before it can send more packets.
[src:red-method/throughput] TCP congestion avoidance controls the data rate.
[src:red-method/throughput] A so-called *slow start* occurs in the beginning of a file transfer, and after packet drops caused by router congestion or bit errors in, for example, wireless links.
[src:red-method/throughput] Ensuring that multiple users can harmoniously share a single communications link requires some kind of equitable sharing of the link.
[src:red-method/throughput] If a communication link offering data rate *R* is shared by *N* active users, ideally, every user can typically achieve a throughput of approximately *R/N*.
[src:red-method/throughput] Network schedulers in routers and switches ultimately determine how bandwidth is shared.
[src:red-method/throughput] If fair queuing is not provided, users that send large packets will get higher bandwidth.
[src:red-method/throughput] Some users may be prioritized in a weighted fair queuing (WFQ) algorithm if differentiated or guaranteed quality of service (QoS) is provided.
[src:red-method/throughput] In some communications systems, such as satellite networks, only a finite number of channels may be available to a given user at a given time.
[src:red-method/throughput] Channels are assigned either through preassignment or through Demand Assigned Multiple Access (DAMA).
[src:red-method/throughput] In these cases, throughput is quantized per channel, and unused capacity on partially utilized channels is lost.
[src:red-method/throughput] The maximum throughput is often an unreliable measurement of effective bandwidth, for example the file transmission data rate in bits per seconds.
[src:red-method/throughput] The achieved throughput is often lower than the maximum throughput.
[src:red-method/throughput] Protocol overhead affects the effective bandwidth.
[src:red-method/throughput] In schemes that include forward error correction codes, the redundant error code is normally excluded from the throughput.
[src:red-method/throughput] An example in modem communication, where the throughput is typically measured in the interface between the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) and the circuit-switched modem connection.
[src:red-method/throughput] In this case, the maximum throughput is often called net bit rate or useful bit rate.
[src:red-method/throughput] To determine the actual data rate of a network or connection, the goodput measurement definition may be used.
[src:red-method/throughput] For example, in file transmission, the goodput corresponds to the file size (in bits) divided by the file transmission time.
[src:red-method/throughput] The goodput is the amount of useful information that is delivered per second to the application layer protocol.
[src:red-method/throughput] Dropped packets or packet retransmissions, as well as protocol overhead, are excluded.
[src:red-method/throughput] Because of that, the goodput is lower than the maximum throughput.
[src:red-method/throughput] Often, a block in a data flow diagram has a single input and a single output, and operates on discrete packets of information.
[src:red-method/throughput] Examples of such blocks are fast Fourier transform modules or binary multipliers.
[src:red-method/throughput] Because the units of throughput (e.g., messages per second) are the reciprocal of the unit for propagation delay (e.g., seconds per message), throughput can be used to relate a computational block to a communications channel, simplifying system analysis.
[src:red-method/throughput] In wireless networks or cellular systems, the system spectral efficiency in bit/s/Hz/area, bit/s/Hz/site or bit/s/Hz/cell units, is the maximum aggregate throughput divided by the analog bandwidth and some measure of the system coverage area.
[src:red-method/throughput] Throughput over analog channels is determined by the modulation scheme, the signal-to-noise ratio, and the available bandwidth.
[src:red-method/throughput] Since throughput is normally defined in terms of quantified digital data, the term *throughput* is not normally used; the term *bandwidth* is more often used instead.
